
[1]excise

   EXCI'SE, n. s as z. [L. excisum, cut off, from excido.]

   An inland duty or impost, laid on commodities consumed, or on the
   retail, which is the last state before consumption; as an excise on
   coffee, soap, candles, which a person consumes in his family. But many
   articles are excised at the manufactories, as spirit at the distillery,
   printed silks and linens at the printer's, &c.

   EXCI'SE, v.t. s as z. To lay or impose a duty on articles consumed, or
   in the hands of merchants, manufacturers and retailers; to levy an
   excise on.
